# Riverpod Patterns

## Context
- Apply when creating or modifying any Riverpod provider, notifier, or consumer widget.
- All providers use `@riverpod` code generation (riverpod_annotation + riverpod_generator).

## Requirements

### Provider Creation
- Annotate with `@riverpod` — never construct `Provider(...)`, `StateNotifierProvider(...)`, etc. manually.
- Provider functions and classes go in `<feature>/providers/` files.
- Each file must declare `part '<filename>.g.dart';` — the generated file.
- Run `dart run build_runner build --delete-conflicting-outputs` after any provider change.

### Notifiers
- Use `AsyncNotifier<T>` for async state (loading/error/data). Use `Notifier<T>` for sync state.
- State type `T` must be a `@freezed` immutable data class or a primitive — never a mutable object.
- Initial state goes in `build()`. Side effects are `Future<void>` methods on the notifier.
- Never expose the internal `state` setter publicly — mutations happen inside the notifier only.

### Consumers
- `ConsumerWidget` for widgets that only read providers (no `ref.listen` side effects).
- `ConsumerStatefulWidget` when you need `initState`/`dispose` alongside Riverpod.
- Call `ref.watch` for reactive rebuilds. Call `ref.read` inside callbacks (e.g., button `onPressed`).
- **Never call `ref.watch` inside a callback** — it only works at build time.
- **Never call `ref.read` at the top of `build()`** for reactive state — use `ref.watch`.

### Error Handling
- `AsyncValue.when(data: ..., loading: ..., error: ...)` — always handle all three cases.
- Never let an unhandled `AsyncError` reach the widget tree silently.
- Errors from providers must map to typed `AppError` subclasses — never expose raw exceptions to the UI.

### Provider Overrides (for testing and dev)
- Inject `StubPaymentService` in development by overriding the payment provider in `ProviderScope`.
- Use `ProviderScope(overrides: [...])` in tests — never reach into providers via global state.

### AppConfig Provider
- `AppConfig` is created once in `main()` and passed to `KioskApp`. Override `appConfigProvider` in the root `ProviderScope`:
  ```dart
  ProviderScope(
    overrides: [appConfigProvider.overrideWithValue(config)],
    child: KioskApp(config: config),
  )
  ```

## Examples

<example>
// Good: @riverpod, AsyncNotifier, typed state
@riverpod
class Payment extends _$Payment {
  @override
  AsyncValue<PaymentState> build(String orderId) => const AsyncData(PaymentIdle());

  Future<void> startPayment() async {
    state = const AsyncData(PaymentProcessing());
    // ...
  }
}
</example>

<example type="invalid">
// Bad: manual provider, mutable state, ref.read in build
final paymentProvider = StateNotifierProvider<PaymentNotifier, PaymentState>(...);
// Bad: ref.watch inside callback
onPressed: () { ref.watch(cartProvider); }
// Bad: ref.read at top of build for reactive state
final cart = ref.read(cartProvider); // won't rebuild on change
</example>

## Critical Rules
- NEVER construct providers manually — always use `@riverpod`.
- NEVER call `ref.watch` inside callbacks.
- NEVER call `ref.read` at top of `build()` for reactive state.
- ALWAYS run build_runner after provider changes.
- ALWAYS handle all three `AsyncValue` cases (data, loading, error).
